{
    "name": "Vaultbreaker Ooze",
    "type": "creature",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Vaultbreaker Ooze",
            "type": "section",
            "text": "Though many oozes hunt among the dreary confines of underground caverns, dungeons, and abandoned ruins, others seek to quell their hunger in areas well-trafficked by civilized creatures. The aptly named vaultbreaker oozes exhibit a mindless compulsion to feed on and digest precious metals. When near precious metals, the ichor exuded from their metallic plasm tarnishes black and forms small, jagged crystals that dot the oozes' surface. Like a strange biological compass, these crystals point vaultbreaker oozes to their next meal.<br/><br/> Though mindless, these strange oozes exhibit an innate instinct for picking and bypassing locks to reach their meals by inserting a gelatinous pseudopod into a keyhole and then hardening the appendage into solid metal, forming a tool similar to a skeleton key.<br/><br/> Vaultbreaker oozes can often be found in cities where tectonic instability has created fissures and cracks, allowing them to infiltrate basements, vaults, and underground chambers that may contain treasure. When rumors of vaultbreaker ooze sightings surface, banker consortiums, Abadaran priests, and even local thieves guilds offer hefty sums to have the dangerous oozes destroyed\u2014though some might instead offer a bounty for their capture.<br/><br/><b><u><a aonid=\"5\" game-obj=\"Skills\" general=\"true\">Recall Knowledge - Ooze</a></u> (<u><a aonid=\"11\" game-obj=\"Skills\">Occultism</a></u>)</b>: DC 24",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Pathfinder #158: Sixty Feet Under",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Pathfinder #158: Sixty Feet Under pg. 87",
                        "alt": "Pathfinder #158: Sixty Feet Under pg. 87",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq022ci"
                    },
                    "page": 87
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "name": "Ooze",
            "type": "section",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "name": "Amoebas Large and Small",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "<a aonid=\"751\" game-obj=\"Monsters\">Giant amoebas</a> and <a aonid=\"750\" game-obj=\"Monsters\">amoeba swarms</a> are usually found near each other, as the two oozes are part of the same life cycle. When a giant amoeba grows large enough, it can spontaneously split apart into two separate amoeba swarms, and when an amoeba swarm feeds enough, its individual components can fuse together into a single creature.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "related_creatures",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Related Creatures",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Related Creatures",
                        "image": "Sidebar_4_RelatedCreatures.png"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "name": "Oozing Acid",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "Many oozes have acidic attacks that can quickly degrade flesh, wood, and even stronger materials. Some believe that oozes are the result of alchemical or magical experimentation run amok, while others postulate that they simply emerged from the natural processes of evolution.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "name": "Other Oozes",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "Many varieties of these nearly mindless predators exist in the world. Some are mere variants, with different colored puddings, jellies, and oozes with little to differentiate them from those presented here other than their habitat. Others are more specialized, or even dangerously intelligent. The <a aonid=\"368\" game-obj=\"Monsters\">shoggoth</a> is one such example, but another variety of deadly and powerful ooze is the thankfully rare blight, a creature composed of protoplasm and eyes that curses entire regions with its presence.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "related_creatures",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Related Creatures",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Related Creatures",
                        "image": "Sidebar_4_RelatedCreatures.png"
                    }
                }
            ],
            "text": "Slimes, molds, and other oozes can be found in dank dungeons and shadowed forests. While not necessarily evil, some grow to enormous sizes and have insatiable appetites.",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Bestiary",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                        "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                    },
                    "page": 254
                }
            ]
        }
    ],
